|= |=

Invariant Rationalization. We ascribe the limitation to ignoring Y S | C in Equation 1, which is crucial to reï¬ne the causal relationship C â†’ Y that is invariant across different S. By introducing this independence, we formalize the task of invariant rationalization as:

min
hCËœ ,hYË†

R(hYË†

â—¦ hCËœ (G), Y ),

s.t. Y

SËœ | CËœ,

(3)

where SËœ = G \ CËœ is the complement of CËœ. This formulation encourages the rationale CËœ seeking the patterns that are stable across different distributions, while discarding the unstable patterns.

2.3 PRINCIPLE & LEARNING STRATEGY OF DIR

Interventional Distribution. However, it is difï¬cult to recover the oracle rationale from the joint distribution over the inputs and labels â€” that is, the causal and non-causal relations are hardly distinguished from each other. We get inspirations from invariant learning (Arjovsky et al., 2019; Krueger et al., 2021; Chang et al., 2020), which constructs different environments to infer the invariant features or predictors. To obtain the environments, previous studies mostly partition the training set by prior knowledge (Teney et al., 2020) or adversarial environment inference (Creager et al., 2021; Wang et al., 2021b). Different from partitioning the training data, we do not assume prophets about environments but introduce the interventional distribution (Tian et al., 2006; Pearl et al., 2016) instead to model the DIR task. Speciï¬cally, on the top of our SCM, we generate s-interventional distribution by doing intervention do(S = s) on S, which removes every link from the parents P A(S) to the variable S and ï¬xes S to the speciï¬c value s. By stratifying different values S = {s}, we can obtain multiple s-interventional distributions.
With interventional distributions, we propose the principle of discovering invariant rationale (DIR) to identify a rationale CËœ whose relationship with the label Y is stable across different distributions.

Deï¬nition 1 (DIR Principle) An intrinsically-interpretable model h satisï¬es the DIR principle if it

1. minimizes all s-interventional risks: Es[R(h(G), Y |do(S = s))], and simultaneously 2. minimizes the variance of various s-interventional risks: Vars({R(h(G), Y |do(S = s))}), where the s-interventional risk is deï¬ned over the s-interventional distribution for speciï¬c s âˆˆ S. Guided by the proposed principle, we design the learning strategy of DIR as:

min RDIR = Es[R(h(G), Y |do(S = s))] + Î»Vars({R(h(G), Y |do(S = s))}),

(4)

where R (h(G), Y | do(S = s)) computes the risk under the s-interventional distribution, which we will elaborate in Section 2.4. Var(Â·) calculates the variance of risks over different s-interventional distributions; Î» is a hyper-parameter to control the strength of invariant learning.

Justiï¬cation. We theoretically justify the DIR principleâ€™s ability to discover invariant rationales. Speciï¬cally, Theorem 1 shows that the oracle model fY respects the DIR principle. Moreover, we suggest that C can be inferred by making the intrinsically interpretable model h conform to the DIR principle under the uniqueness condition (cf. Corollary 1). We leave the detailed proofs in Appendix
C due to the limited space. By making the distribution-relevant risks indifferent while pursuing low risks, the DIR principle is able to discover the invariant rationales CËœ as the approximation of the oracle rationales C, while encouraging hYË† approaching the oracle model fY .

2.4 DIR-GUIDED IMPLEMENTATION OF INTRINSICALLY-INTERPRETABLE GNNS

With the DIR principle and objective, we present how to implement the intrinsically-interpretable GNNs. We summarize the key notations of this section in Appendix A for clarity. Following Equation 2, a model h with intrinsic interpretability consists of two modules: h = hYË† â—¦ hCËœ, where hCËœ is to extract a possible rationale, and hYË† is to make prediction based on the rationale. Moreover, to establish the s-interventional distributions, we design an additional module to do the interventions. In a nutshell, our framework consists of four components, as Figure 3 shows.
Rationale Generator. It aims to split the input graph instance g into two subgraphs: causal part cËœ and non-causal part sËœ. Speciï¬cally, given an input graph instance g = (V, E) with the node set V

