and the edge set E, its adjacency matrix is A âˆˆ {0, 1}|V|Ã—|V|, where Aij = 1 denotes the edge from node i to node j, and Aij = 0 otherwise. The rationale generator ï¬rst adopts a GNN to generate the mask matrix M âˆˆ R|V|Ã—|V| on A, where mask Mij indicates the importance of edge Aij:

Z = GNN1(g), Mij = Ïƒ(Zi Zj),

(5)

where Ïƒ(Â·) is the sigmoid function and Z âˆˆ R|V|Ã—d summarizes the d-dimensional representations of all nodes. The generator then selects the edges with the highest masks to construct the rationale cËœ and collects cËœâ€™s complement as sËœ, as follows:

EcËœ = Topr(M A), EsËœ = Top1âˆ’r((1 âˆ’ M) A),

(6)

where EcËœ and EsËœ are the edge sets of cËœ and sËœ, respectively; Topr(Â·) selects the top-K edges with K = r Ã— |E|, and r is the hyper-parameter (e.g., 40%); is the element-wise product. Having obtained the edge sets, we can distill the nodes appearing in the edges to establish cËœ and sËœ.

Distribution Intervener. It targets at creating interventional distributions. Formally, it ï¬rst collects the non-causal part of all the instances into a memory bank as SËœ. It next samples a memory sËœi âˆˆ SËœ to conduct the intervention do(S = sËœi), replacing the complement of the critical subgraph cËœj at hand and constructing an intervened pair (cËœj, sËœi), where i, j are indices.
Graph Encoder & Classiï¬ers . Here we represent hYË† as a combination of a graph encoder and two classiï¬ers. Speciï¬cally, it employs another GNN encoder on cËœ to generate node representations ZcËœ âˆˆ R|V|Ã—d, and then combines them as graph representation HcËœ âˆˆ RD via a global pooling operator, e.g., average pooling. Then it uses a classiï¬er Î¦c to project the graph representation into a probability distribution over class labels yË†cËœ. More formally, the process is as follows:

ZcËœ = GNN2(cËœ), HcËœ = Pooling(ZcËœ), yË†cËœ = Î¦c(HcËœ).

(7)

Analogously, we can obtain yË†sËœ for sËœ via the shared encoder and another classiï¬er Î¦s. yË†cËœ is the pre-

diction based merely on the causal part cËœ, while yË†sËœ measures the predictive power of the intervened part sËœ. Inspired by Cade`ne et al. (2019), we formulate the joint prediction yË† under the intervention

do(S = sËœ) as yË†cËœ masked by yË†sËœ:

yË† = yË†cËœ Ïƒ(yË†sËœ),

(8)

where the sigmoid function adjusts the output logits of cËœ to compensate for the spurious biases. In Appendix E, we present examples of how this operation helps discover the causal part.

Optimization. Having established the prediction yË† of an instance g under the intervention do(S = sËœ), we are capable of getting the sËœ-interventional risk similar as Equation 4 as follows:

R(h(G), Y |do(S = sËœ)) = E(g,y)âˆˆO,S=sËœ,C=hCËœ (g)l(yË†, y),

(9)

where (g, y) âˆˆ O is a pair of graph instance g and its ground-truth label y from the training set O; l(Â·) denotes the loss function on a single instance. Moreover, we deï¬ne the loss for Î¦s module as:

RSËœ = E(g,y)âˆˆO,sËœ=g/hCËœ (g)l(yË†sËœ, y)

(10)

Speciï¬cally, RSËœ is only backpropagated to the classiï¬er Î¦s and we set apart the other components from its backpropagation to avoid interference with representation learning. Thus, this loss promotes
the SËœ-only branch to learn spurious biases given the non-causal features only. Overall, we can jointly

optimize these components via the DIR objective and shortcut loss, i.e.,

