Hence, fY takes the minimum penalty and satisï¬es the DIR Principle.
Notably, if S â†’ C, then Var ({R(fY | do(s)) | s âˆˆ S}) may not equal to zero since c âˆ¼ PI(s)(C|S = s). In such case, fY is not necessarily satisï¬ed to DIR Principle. That is, although fY still minimizes R(f | do(S)), we canâ€™t be sure whether it reaches the lower bound of Var ({R(fY | do(s)) | s âˆˆ S}) without knowledge about the speciï¬c data distribution. Thus, we only consider the cases of C â†’ S, C S and C â† E â†’ S in the following discussion.

|=

Theorem 2 (Uniqueness) Suppose l is a strict loss function and there exists one and only one nontrivial subset C, then there exists a unique structure equation model fY s.t. it satisï¬es the DIR Principle.

Proof: Since fY exists and satisï¬es the DIR Principle, we only need to prove its uniqueness under the given conditions. Otherwise, suppose we have another structure equation fY = fY satiï¬es the DIR Principle. Speciï¬cally, there exists a datum (g, y) s.t. fY (c) = fY (c). Thus, we have l(fY (c), y) > l(fY (c), y). Given that Var ({R(fY | do(s)) | s âˆˆ S}) â‰¥ 0 = Var ({R(fY | do(s)) | s âˆˆ S}), we have RDIR(fY ) > RDIR(fY ).
In reality, there could be multiple candidates of C, e.g., Ci, Cj s.t. RDIR(fY(Ci)) = RDIR(fY(Cj)), where fY(Ci) is the structure equation corresponds to Ci. Thus, it calls for the selection of C to avoid the learning of suboptimal fY . Inspired by Occamâ€™s Razor, we deï¬ne

Câˆ— = arg min |C|

(15)

as the preferred rationale, or rationale of parsimony. We argue that rationales are not to be extended beyond necessity, which poses simpler hypotheses about causality. As the search of Câˆ— is NP-
hard (the worst time complexity is exponential), we use ï¬xed size for the learned rationales in our
experiments and leave a better optimization to future work.

Corollary 1 (Necessity and Sufï¬ciency) Suppose l is a strict loss function and there exists one and only one non-trival subset C, then any structure causal model fY s.t. it satisï¬es the DIR Principle iff. fY = fY .
This is directly obtained from Theorem 2. Thus, under the unique constraint of C, we can approach the oracle fY by optimizing the DIR objective, which maintains the invariant causal relation between the causal feature and the response variable Y . In another way, based on the uniqueness of the feasible rationale, the optimization of the DIR Principle on the intrinsic interpretable model h (where C is exhibited inside of h) pushes the approach to C with rationales CËœ. Then, fY can also be approached as an invariant predictor based on the learning from CËœ.

