/

Datasets We summarize dataset statistics in Table 3, and introduce the node/edge features and the preprocessing in each datasets:
â€¢ Spurious-Motif. We use random node features and constant edge weights in this dataset.
â€¢ MNIST-75sp. The nodes in the graphs are superpixels, and node features are the concatenation of pixel intensities (RGB channels) and coordinates of their mass centers. Edges are the spatial distance between the superpixel centers, while we ï¬lter the edges with a distance less than 0.1 to make the graphs sparser.
â€¢ Graph-SST2. We use constant edge weight and ï¬lter the graphs with edges less than three. We initialize the node features by the pre-trained BERT (Devlin et al., 2018) word embedding.
â€¢ OGBG-Molhiv. We use the ofï¬cial released dataset in our experiment.
GNNs. We summarize the backbone GNNs for each dataset in Table 3. The number of neurons in the sequent layers (in forwarding order) is reported. We use ReLU as activation layers and different global pooling layers. In OGBG-Molhiv, we adopt one fully connected layer for the prediction layers while using two fully connected layers for the models in other datasets. For baselines with node pooling/node attention, we add one node pooling/attention layer in the second convolution layer.
Training Optimization & Early Stopping. All experiments are done on a single Tesla V100 SXM2 GPU (32 GB). During training, we use Adam (Kingma & Ba, 2015) optimizer. The maximum number of epochs is 400 for all datasets. We use Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD) for the optimization on Graph-SST2 and OGBG-Molhiv and Gradient Descent (GD) for the other two datasets. Also, we exhibit early stopping to avoid overï¬tting of the training dataset. Speciï¬cally, in MNIST-75sp, Graph-SST2 and OGBG-Molhiv, each model is evaluated on a holdout in-distribution validation dataset after each epoch. While for Spurious-Motif, we use an unbiased validation dataset (i.e., without spurious relations compared to the training dataset). If the modelâ€™s performance on the validation dataset is without improvement (i.e., validation accuracy begins to decrease) for ï¬ve epochs, we stop the training process to prevent increased generalization error.
Hyper-Parameter Settings. We set the causal feature ratio and Î» as (r = 0.8, Î» = 10âˆ’4), (r = 0.25, Î» = 10âˆ’2), (r = 0.6, Î» = 102), (r = 0.8, Î» = 10âˆ’3) for MNIST-75sp, Spurious-Motif, Graph-SST2 and OGBG-Molhiv respectively. For other baselines, we adopt grid search for the best parameters using the validation datasets.
Model Selection. We select each model based on its performance on the corresponding validation dataset. We repeat each experiment at least ï¬ve times and report the average values and the standard errors in the paper.
18

Published as a conference paper at ICLR 2022
E UNIMODAL ADJUSTMENT
We follow Cade`ne et al. (2019) to demonstrate how the shortcut prediction can help to remove model bias. For clarity, we refer to the model parameters except for Î¦2 as the main branch, i.e., except for the S-only branch. Given a house-tree graph as the input graph, we suppose the shortcut prediction yË†sËœ of the tree subgraph leans towards the house class. Then after reweighting Ïƒ(yË†sËœ) on yË†cËœ, the softmax readout on the house class in the joint prediction yË† will be magniï¬ed, which results in a smaller loss backpropagated to the main branch and prevents yË†cËœ from inductive bias. In another situation where a house-wheel graph is given as the input, we similarly suppose the shortcut prediction yË†sËœ of the wheel subgraph leans towards other classes except the house, say, the circle class. Then after reweighting Ïƒ(yË†sËœ) on yË†cËœ, the softmax readout on the house class in the joint prediction yË† will be reduced, which results in a larger loss back-propagated to the main branch and encourages the model to learn from these examples. Furthermore, we offer the causal- and information-theoretical justiï¬cations: (1) From the perspective of causal theory (Pearl, 2000; Pearl et al., 2016), the element-wise multiplication enforces the spurious prediction to estimate the pure indirect effect (PIE) of the shortcut features, while the causal prediction captures the natural direct effect (NDE) of the causal patterns (VanderWeele, 2013); (2) From the perspective of information theory (Kullback, 1997), the element-wise multiplication makes the causal prediction reï¬‚ect the conditional mutual information between the causal patterns and ground-truths, conditioning on the complement patterns.
