Figure 10: Sensitivity of Hyper-Parameter Î». In each chart, dash line represents the performance of the best baseline in the corresponding dataset, and the area between ACCÂ±std are colored.
We analyze the performance of DIR w.r.t. the hyper-parameter Î». As shown in Figure 10, with Î» â†’ 0, DIR degrades to optimize the performance in each environment only, without explicitly penalizing the shortcutsâ€™ inï¬‚uence on the model predictions. We also see that all testing performances drop sharply if Î» is too large. Since a large weight on the variance term emphasis on the invariance condition while leading to the overlook on the performance loss, it could fail to exhibit fYËœ correctly. Notably, such a trade-off in the DIR objective is commonly shared among all the datasets.

