However, we show that spurious classiï¬ers are over-conï¬dent and potentially overï¬t to spurious features, which fails to generalize out-of-distribution. In Table 5, we evaluate the spurious classiï¬ers (taking non-causal features as inputs) on the testing sets. We argue that the performance degradation is caused by (i) feature-level problem: it could be theoretically inadequate to infer the label given the non-causal features, and (ii) paradigm-level problem: minimizing the empirical risk only can hardly exhibit stable relations between the features and labels.

